          <text>
            The freighter appears in the sky just after dawn.

            I stand outside the facility with Scout, watching it descend. The whole community is gatherednot crowding, justpresent, supporting me, whatever happens.

            Scout bouncesnervous, exciteda big moment bounce.

            I say, "Big moment."

            The commercial freighter Harmony Prospect lands smoothlya professional operation. Two figures emerge: Captain Torres and a woman who looks like a medical officer.

            I walk forward to meet themcalm, certain.

            I say, "Captain Torres. Thank you for coming."

            Torres is tall, efficient-looking, clearly used to command. He says, "Kira Voss? Survivor of courier vessel crash?"

            I answer, "That's me."

            He says, "We're here to extract you and return you to human civilization. Are you ready to depart?"

            Here it isthe moment.

            ¶

            I say clearly, "Thank you for comingbut I'm choosing to stay here. This is my home."

            Torres blinks. He says, "I'm sorry, what?"

            I say, "I'm choosing to remain with this community. I'm not being held. This is my free decision."

            The medical officerDr. Chen, according to her badgesteps forward immediately. She says, "We need to evaluate you. After weeks stranded, there could be psychological effects, Stockholm syndrome, alien influence"

            I say, "You're welcome to scan me. I'm neurologically sound, fully lucid, and making this choice freely."

            Dr. Chen pulls out a medical scanner and runs it over me. She frowns at the readings and says, "Vitals normal. No foreign substances. Neural patterns indicateyou're actually healthier than baseline."

            I say, "I told you."

            Torres is processing this. He says, "Ms. Voss, you've been stranded with alien life forms for weeks. It's natural to form attachment to your rescuers, but"

            I say, "They're not my rescuers. They're my community."

            He says, "They're plants."

            I say, "They're people who value my individual contributionwhich is more than I can say for the human bureaucracy that sent me on that courier mission."

            Torres looks past me at the facilitythe weird, wonderful plant construction, the artistic growth, the absurd but functional design. He says, "This isn't an appropriate environment for a human."

            I keep my voice calm, rational. I say, "It's more appropriate than any environment I've lived in. Captain, I understand this is irregular. But I'm a legal adult, sound mind, making an informed choiceI'm choosing to stay."

            He begins, "We have regulations"

            I finish, "About rescue refusal? Yes. I'm refusing rescue. Not because I'm impaired or coerced. Because I found something rare: authentic belonging."

            Dr. Chen continues scanning. She says, "Her well-being indicators are significantly elevated. Stress levels below norm, social integration metrics high, psychological markers all positive."

            I say simply, "That's because I'm happy here."

            Torres struggles with this. He says, "The company sent us to extract a human survivor. Standard protocol"

            I finish, "Doesn't cover this situation. I know. But I'm still choosing to stay."
          </text>
